{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17491074","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17491074"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-29T05:31:11+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-29T05:31:11+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"824"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"824","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/824"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.77,0.08,0.09,0.02,0.04]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"824"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"103538"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"824","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/824"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"824"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"85954"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"2"},{"type":"tags","id":"25"},{"type":"tags","id":"66"},{"type":"tags","id":"72"},{"type":"tags","id":"98"},{"type":"tags","id":"106"},{"type":"tags","id":"2602"},{"type":"tags","id":"4953"},{"type":"tags","id":"4977"},{"type":"tags","id":"4987"},{"type":"tags","id":"4988"},{"type":"tags","id":"9735"},{"type":"tags","id":"11625"},{"type":"tags","id":"11626"},{"type":"tags","id":"11640"},{"type":"tags","id":"11650"},{"type":"tags","id":"11676"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"1790"},{"type":"contributions","id":"1801"},{"type":"contributions","id":"42159"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"103538","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/103538"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EA 70-year-old woman presents to the General Practice clinic with a three-week history of palpitations and dizziness. Her medical history includes hypertension and previous peptic ulcer disease, treated with ramipril and esomeprazole, respectively. She always remembers to take her medications on time. At home, she enjoys growing vegetables in her garden. Blood tests reveal an estimated glomerular filtration rate of 76 mL/min/1.73m\u003Csup\u003E2\u003C/sup\u003E (60-120), creatinine 68 \u0026micro;mol/L (45-90), and urea 5.2 mmol/L (2.5-7.0). A 24-hour Holter monitor detects paroxysmal atrial fibrillation and a subsequent echocardiogram confirms no valvular disease and a normal ejection fraction.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following is the most appropriate medication to commence her on?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Apixaban","Aspirin","Warfarin","Dipyridamole","Enoxaparin"],"correctOptions":[0],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThis patient has been diagnosed with atrial fibrillation and requires anticoagulation, due to her age and history of hypertension. Based on both of these factors, her CHA2DS2-VA score is 2 (oral anticoagulants are recommended if score is 2 or more and should be considered if score is 1). Note that the National Heart Foundation Australia\u0027s atrial fibrillation guidelines no longer include sex category in the calculation of the score. This has simplified the task of determining stroke risk and the need for anticoagulation therapy in a patient with atrial fibrillation.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EApixaban\u003C/strong\u003E is the most suitable agent, making this the correct answer. Apixaban belongs to the direct acting oral anticoagulant class, and is a non-reversible inhibitor of factor Xa. She is likely to be compliant with this medication and her renal function is good, so there are no contraindications to commencing therapy.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EAspirin\u003C/strong\u003E and \u003Cstrong\u003Edipyridamole\u003C/strong\u003E are antiplatelet agents, and monotherapy with either is far less effective than oral anticoagulants in preventing stroke in patients with atrial fibrillation.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EWhilst \u003Cstrong\u003Ewarfarin\u003C/strong\u003E might be a good choice, particularly if there was valvular atrial fibrillation, renal dysfunction and/or poor compliance with medication (international normalised ratio is regularly monitored, giving an indication of compliance), neither of these issues are present in this case. Furthermore, ingestion of compounds containing vitamin K (such as green leafy vegetables) can lead to sub-therapeutic international normalised ratio, which might be relevant in this patient due to her gardening hobby. Warfarin has also been associated with a higher risk of intracranial haemorrhage than apixaban. For all of these reasons, warfarin is also incorrect.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EEnoxaparin\u003C/strong\u003E (low molecular weight heparin) is an injection administered subcutaneously. It is most commonly used as deep vein thrombosis prophylaxis in the hospital setting and mainly on a short-term basis. It is sometimes used in community settings, for example in patients recovering from major orthopaedic surgery or in those with active malignancy. Enoxaparin is not a realistic option in this case, as the patient requires anticoagulation on an ongoing basis.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":null,"learningPoints":["Direct acting oral anticoagulants are preferred for stroke prevention in non-valvular atrial fibrillation.","Antiplatelet agents are less effective than anticoagulants for stroke prevention in atrial fibrillation.","Warfarin may be considered in specific situations such as valvular atrial fibrillation or significant renal impairment."],"references":["Rajan R, Jarallah MA, Jayakumar RB,  Loricchio ML, Dashti R, Hemeda AA. Treating atrial fibrillation with antiplatelet drugs in the elderly: pro and contra arguments. e-Journal of Cardiology Practice [internet]. 2019 Mar [cited 2021 Feb 20]; 17(3)Vol.17 no.3 Mar 2019. Available from:https://www.escardio.org/Journals/E-Journal-of-Cardiology-Practice/Volume-17/treating-atrial-fibrillation-with-antiplatelet-drugs-in-the-elderly-pro-and-contra-arguments","Lopes RD, Al-Khatib SM, Wallentin L, Yang H, Ansell J, Bahit C, et al. Efficacy and safety of apixaban compared with warfarin according to patient risk of stroke and of bleeding in atrial fibrillation: a secondary analysis of a randomised controlled trial. The Lancet. 2012 Nov;380(9855): 1749-58","Verma KP, Wong M. Atrial fibrillation. Australian Journal of General Practice [internet]. 2019 Oct;48(10).Available from:https://www1.racgp.org.au/ajgp/2019/october/atrial-fibrillation DOI:10.31128/AJGP-12-18-4787"]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"85954"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"824"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"85954","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/85954"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2025-05-23T14:24:26+09:30","updatedAt":"2025-05-23T14:24:35+09:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"824"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"103538"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"2","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/2"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83e\udec0","name":"Cardiology","synonyms":[],"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":"2024-11-21T09:47:21+10:30"},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"1"}},"heading":{"data":{"type":"tagHeadings","id":"1"}}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"25","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/25"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83d\udc68\u200d\ud83d\udc69\u200d\ud83d\udc66","name":"General Practice","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id